<paragraph blockId="148.[128,654,1469,1759]" lastBlockId="148.[701,1227,213,324]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
DISCUSSION: 
<bibRefCitation author="Scudder, S. H." box="[313,488,1470,1493]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" pagination="1 - 734" refId="ref129828" refString="Scudder, S. H. 1890. The Tertiary iInsects of North America. Report of the United States Geological Survey of the Territories 13: 1 - 734." type="journal article" year="1890">Scudder (1890)</bibRefCitation>
described this species from Oligocene deposits of Florissant (
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter, F. M." box="[136,340,1530,1552]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" refId="ref126076" refString="Carpenter, F. M. 1992. Treatise on invertebrate paleontology. Part R. Arthropoda 4. Vol. 3: Superclass Hexapoda. Peace: Geological Society of America, and University of Kansas, xxii + 277 pp." type="book" year="1992">Carpenter, 1992</bibRefCitation>
). He stated a probable affinity of the fossil species with the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forero" authorityYear="2008" box="[128,262,1588,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hadronema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[128,262,1588,1611]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Hadronema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and pointed out the ‘‘doubtful’’ position within the genus. The outline drawing and deficient description presented by Scudder prevent further conclusions about the identity of this species. The 
<typeStatus box="[554,653,1708,1729]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">syntypes</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Scudder, S. H." box="[135,304,1737,1759]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" pagination="1 - 734" refId="ref129828" refString="Scudder, S. H. 1890. The Tertiary iInsects of North America. Report of the United States Geological Survey of the Territories 13: 1 - 734." type="journal article" year="1890">Scudder, 1890</bibRefCitation>
) deposited at the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard have not been examined. No other fossil species has been included in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Carpenter, 1992)" baseAuthorityName="Carpenter" baseAuthorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hadronema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[939,1073,271,294]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Hadronema</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter, F. M." pageId="148" pageNumber="149" refId="ref126076" refString="Carpenter, F. M. 1992. Treatise on invertebrate paleontology. Part R. Arthropoda 4. Vol. 3: Superclass Hexapoda. Peace: Geological Society of America, and University of Kansas, xxii + 277 pp." type="book" year="1992">Carpenter, 1992</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
